WEBVTT

00:00:00.640 --> 00:00:06.880
Good afternoon. I'm JooYoung Seo. I'm an assistant professor in the School of Information Sciences

00:00:06.880 --> 00:00:12.720
at the University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign, and I'm also the director of Accessibility Design

00:00:12.720 --> 00:00:19.840
Lab, where I design and develop data science tools, inclusive data science tools and practices

00:00:19.840 --> 00:00:26.879
with my amazing students and collaborators. And there's one more thing about me.

00:00:27.840 --> 00:00:33.840
I'm a blind professor who teaches data science and data visualization to my sighted students.

00:00:34.799 --> 00:00:43.759
So if that makes you pause, good, because it reveals an assumption that vision is the only

00:00:43.759 --> 00:00:51.200
reliable path to insight. Over the next 20 minutes, I want to challenge that premise.

00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:58.320
So let's think about it. What good is a chart that you can't see?

00:01:00.160 --> 00:01:07.279
How do you read a chart that you can't see? So now when you hear these two questions,

00:01:07.839 --> 00:01:15.680
you might feel a bit puzzled. That's because the data visualization inherently assumes that you

00:01:15.839 --> 00:01:23.519
assumes that you have the ability to see. We often can't separate the idea of visual

00:01:24.720 --> 00:01:28.559
ability from how we think about data visualization.

00:01:31.199 --> 00:01:36.160
For sighted users, data visualization is an incredible, powerful tool.

00:01:37.599 --> 00:01:42.160
So there's that saying, a picture is worth a thousand words.

00:01:42.400 --> 00:01:48.639
And through data visualization, you can get instant insights and a much clearer understanding

00:01:48.639 --> 00:01:55.440
of complex data. It's a fantastic communication tool. But what about users with visual impairments

00:01:55.440 --> 00:02:05.519
just like me? For them, data visualization that assumes visual ability is like a wall

00:02:06.000 --> 00:02:15.600
of inaccessible information. It's a locked door behind which valuable insights are trapped.

00:02:17.839 --> 00:02:21.679
In that sense, data visualization becomes a barrier to understanding

00:02:22.559 --> 00:02:28.720
for users with visual impairments. So that's why I like to call this as

00:02:29.279 --> 00:02:38.080
data visualization divide. In our data science community, we've long tackled this issue

00:02:39.679 --> 00:02:49.279
with what I call a design for them approach. So basically, a sighted person creates a visual

00:02:49.839 --> 00:02:58.479
So basically, a sighted person creates a visual chart. And then as an afterthought,

00:02:59.199 --> 00:03:05.199
they might add a separate text description, also known as alternative text, alt text,

00:03:07.119 --> 00:03:13.759
for blind and screen reader users. But the problem with this design for them approach

00:03:14.559 --> 00:03:25.600
is that it creates just one way street problem. So one group produces and sets the boundaries

00:03:26.639 --> 00:03:32.160
while the other group just consumes. Just consume whatever is handed to them.

00:03:34.160 --> 00:03:39.199
So this kind of power imbalance means that blind or screen reader users

00:03:39.839 --> 00:03:46.160
are just stuck within the boundaries defined by sighted creators.

00:03:48.160 --> 00:03:58.160
So now, I think it's time for us to shift from the conventional design for them approach to a,

00:03:58.160 --> 00:04:07.759
what I call design for us approach. So designing for everyone and making a two-way street for

00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:19.040
everyone is a collaborator. So by the time I say this, you may think, well, that sounds like a

00:04:19.040 --> 00:04:29.519
great idea, but it also sounds a bit, a little bit idealistic. How are you going to actually

00:04:29.519 --> 00:04:38.160
do this? So that's a big question. So well, today, I'm going to introduce you the solution.

00:04:41.279 --> 00:04:49.519
The solution is called MATER. It's a design framework that I've been working on for the

00:04:49.519 --> 00:04:54.959
past few years with my amazing colleagues as students at the University of Illinois.

00:04:55.920 --> 00:05:05.359
MATER is a multi-modal access and interactive data representation framework. It decouples a

00:05:05.359 --> 00:05:17.200
vision-first assumption from data interpretation, and it encodes multi-modalities into the data.

00:05:17.600 --> 00:05:26.559
So it doesn't create a separate or watered-down version for only for screen reader or blind

00:05:26.559 --> 00:05:33.279
users. Instead, everyone uses the same tool, unified tool, and experience the same insight.

00:05:36.880 --> 00:05:43.839
So it doesn't give up on visualization. Instead, it builds on top of the visualization

00:05:44.720 --> 00:05:51.119
by encoding multi-modalities like touchable braille, readable text,

00:05:51.119 --> 00:05:59.920
audible sonification, and conversational AI. So let's take a look at each of the features.

00:05:59.920 --> 00:06:06.320
So first, you can fill the data using touchable braille, touchable representation.

00:06:07.279 --> 00:06:15.839
So what that means is that we can represent data patterns in Unicode braille. So for users with a

00:06:15.839 --> 00:06:21.760
braille display, refreshable braille display, they can actually fill the peaks and valleys of the

00:06:21.760 --> 00:06:33.200
data with their fingertips. As presented on the table on the screen, the idea is that as the data

00:06:33.279 --> 00:06:41.040
values increase, we use higher braille patterns. And as the values decrease, we use lower braille

00:06:41.040 --> 00:06:53.200
patterns. So this screen I'm showing you, it demonstrates how it works. And in the bottom

00:06:53.200 --> 00:07:00.799
right corner, you can see the hardware that people with visual impairments use. It's called a

00:07:00.799 --> 00:07:07.760
refreshable braille display that can represent the braille Unicode pattern physically so that

00:07:07.760 --> 00:07:17.600
they can feel through a fingertip. So next, we can listen to the data with audible representation.

00:07:18.239 --> 00:07:23.679
So this technique is called sonification, data sonification. What that means is that we can map

00:07:24.239 --> 00:07:29.359
data pattern into musical representation. So for example,

00:07:31.519 --> 00:07:41.760
we can map the x-axis to left to right stereo panning. And we can represent increasing or

00:07:41.760 --> 00:07:52.480
decreasing y values pattern with different pitches. So here's an example. On the left side of the

00:07:52.480 --> 00:08:02.959
screen, you may see a conventional, a strong positive correlation between x and y variable.

00:08:03.839 --> 00:08:06.880
And this is what it sounds like.

00:08:07.839 --> 00:08:23.440
So you may hear the gradually increasing tone from left to right that can represent the positive

00:08:24.399 --> 00:08:33.119
correlation. Next, we can understand the data with readable text. This one is simple and

00:08:33.119 --> 00:08:40.719
straightforward. So what that means is that we can provide summaries or values in text format.

00:08:42.719 --> 00:08:50.080
And finally, we can chat with data using conversational AI and everyday

00:08:50.799 --> 00:08:56.159
large language model like GPT or Cloud and Jebedi.

00:08:59.280 --> 00:09:05.599
Okay, so I've explained all about MATER theoretically.

00:09:09.520 --> 00:09:17.840
Beyond theory, let's take a look and let's see how MATER works. So MATER in action.

00:09:20.320 --> 00:09:31.760
So today, I'm so proud to be able to introduce a Python implementation of MATER. I'm sorry for

00:09:31.760 --> 00:09:40.080
our lovers. But here are three very simple steps to create a multimodal representation. Step one,

00:09:40.080 --> 00:09:50.080
import MATER package, which is available in PyPI. And step two, create your plot using

00:09:50.080 --> 00:10:01.359
Matplotlib or Seaborn. And step three, show using MATER.show, just like how you do using PLT.show.

00:10:02.320 --> 00:10:12.320
And just like this Python code. So part one and part three, these are the two simple changes you

00:10:12.320 --> 00:10:18.239
need to introduce to your existing code. So you may have a question, oh, are you kidding? No

00:10:18.239 --> 00:10:28.239
kidding. Actually, this is really all it takes. And once you use these two simple lines of code,

00:10:29.119 --> 00:10:36.640
your existing Matplotlib and Seaborn chart will be automatically translated into a multimodal chart.

00:10:43.039 --> 00:10:49.200
So this is just a keyboard shortcut key. Once it's rendered into your web browser,

00:10:49.200 --> 00:10:54.960
you can toggle on and off braille using single letter key before braille.

00:10:55.919 --> 00:11:04.080
And T for text and S for sonification. And question mark for AI chat.

00:11:04.080 --> 00:11:11.359
So let's take a look at some examples.

00:11:17.280 --> 00:11:26.239
So we have a conventional multiline example written in Matplotlib. And once it's rendered,

00:11:26.479 --> 00:11:37.520
it creates interactive SVG chart like this. So I'm going to switch my sound card so that you

00:11:37.520 --> 00:11:55.440
can hear my screen reader sound as well. So I'm going to use left to right arrow key.

00:11:56.239 --> 00:12:14.159
So it has three lines. Population index. Life expectancy index.

00:12:15.119 --> 00:12:24.080
GDP per capita. So each line has distinct audio.

00:12:35.119 --> 00:12:42.719
So that blind people can see here with a musical note. And then it has braille

00:12:42.719 --> 00:12:51.599
representation. I just press B. So when I move around, the braille representation

00:12:51.599 --> 00:13:03.280
is synced with a visible highlight. And I can even have a conversation.

00:13:03.280 --> 00:13:26.080
So when I press question mark, describe this to a person and hit enter.

00:13:27.039 --> 00:13:28.880
And it's processing.

00:13:43.840 --> 00:13:51.119
So we send the same prompt to two different models. AI, open AI, GPT, and Gemini.

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:59.119
And even users can configure the model. The reason is that blind people cannot easily verify,

00:13:59.119 --> 00:14:07.359
so that by giving them multiple responses, we wanted them to have more informed decision.

00:14:07.359 --> 00:14:25.440
So what about box plot? So box plot is also rendered in the multimodal format.

00:14:26.400 --> 00:14:43.200
And this is a braille. And you can compare GDP per capita between Africa and Europe

00:14:43.200 --> 00:14:49.039
using different tones. So this one has a higher tone.

00:14:54.479 --> 00:14:59.520
And what about multi-layer? So this is a histogram having two layers.

00:15:00.080 --> 00:15:05.280
The second layer has KD, kernel distribution estimation.

00:15:05.280 --> 00:15:14.159
And we can move between layers by pressing page up or page down. So this is the first layer.

00:15:17.599 --> 00:15:27.280
This is second layer. So second layer, first layer. And all layer has braille representation

00:15:27.280 --> 00:15:33.760
as well. What about more complicated example like multi-panel subplot? Yes,

00:15:33.760 --> 00:15:45.119
it's completely accessible. So I can move around between subplots. Shiny? Yes. It's supported.

00:15:46.080 --> 00:15:56.479
So we have added custom render, made a render. So once it's rendered, Shiny is made fully

00:15:57.119 --> 00:16:08.880
accessible for the matplotlib. So you may wonder how this is possible, what's happening beyond

00:16:08.960 --> 00:16:18.320
this message. We use three different layers. So we capture, we intercept the matplotlib and

00:16:19.119 --> 00:16:27.520
Seaborn, and we extract their data, raw data, and we bake the raw data into SVG.

00:16:28.559 --> 00:16:37.200
And with audible sonification, braille pattern, and we have developed our core JavaScript engine

00:16:37.200 --> 00:16:53.840
to make it accessible. So you may wonder whether there is any performance issue when we use this

00:16:54.559 --> 00:17:02.080
monkey patching approach. Actually, the performance overhead is very

00:17:02.640 --> 00:17:14.479
manageable. So you can ignore any overhead. Because for matplotlib, it's only 1.48 millisecond

00:17:14.479 --> 00:17:19.920
on average with mater. So this is literally nothing. So millisecond.

00:17:20.479 --> 00:17:35.199
So for matplotlib, it's 1.48. For Seaborn, it's only 3.26 millisecond overhead. So practically,

00:17:35.199 --> 00:17:46.560
this is nothing. So as I demonstrate today, it's not only working for matplotlib and Seaborn

00:17:47.280 --> 00:17:53.040
vanilla code, but it supports reactive dashboard like Shiny and Streamlit.

00:17:53.760 --> 00:18:00.800
And what about reproducible document? Absolutely, it supports Quoto. Because I made this slide with

00:18:00.800 --> 00:18:06.079
Quoto. And what about interactive computing? Interactive computing like Jupyter Notebook

00:18:06.079 --> 00:18:17.599
and Google Colab? Yes, that's supported. So it's time for us to build the future together.

00:18:18.719 --> 00:18:27.599
So mater is not just about tool. It's more than tool. So this is about different perspective.

00:18:28.560 --> 00:18:36.319
So it's about fundamental shift in how we think about communication and visualization.

00:18:40.400 --> 00:18:46.959
So please build the future together. You can start today. You can just pip install mater

00:18:47.040 --> 00:18:59.439
in your terminal. And its source code, open source contribution is available on GitHub.

00:18:59.439 --> 00:19:06.160
And its user manual is also available at py.mater.ai.

00:19:07.119 --> 00:19:16.000
Ji-Jung, I'm so sorry to interrupt you. Would you like to make an end to your presentation?

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:19.520
Or would you like to make a question? Yeah, actually, this is my end.

00:19:20.239 --> 00:19:26.000
Yeah, very well.

